# Fluff Date: 2026-03-07 11:22:50
<overview>
<p>The Galleon Light Tank entered service with the Free Worlds League in 2692, designed by Brooks Incorporated as an economical solution for providing infantry and BattleMech formations with mobile combat support. Produced at multiple plants across the League and on Capellan worlds under license, the Galleon quickly established itself as one of the more affordable light tanks of the Star League era. Its tracked configuration prioritized reliability over terrain flexibility, and its combination of speed and modest firepower made it useful across a wide range of support roles. After the Exodus, the tank spread broadly across the Inner Sphere, with large numbers falling into the hands of the Draconis Combine and the Free Worlds League. It remained in continuous production in various forms through the ilClan era, a testament to the sound engineering of the original Brooks platform and its adaptability to radically different operational requirements.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The GAL-100 uses a GTEM 180 ICE engine to achieve a top speed of approximately 97 kilometers per hour, fast enough to outpace most BattleMechs of comparable weight class. Its armament consists of a single Jackson Model 17 medium laser mounted in the turret and two Model 12 small lasers in side-facing positions. These weapons are produced by Jackson Armaments, a wholly owned subsidiary of Brooks Incorporated, and provide reasonable anti-infantry and light anti-armor capability. The tank carries three and a half tons of StarSlab ferro-fibrous armor, adequate against small arms and light weapons but vulnerable to sustained fire from heavier designs.</p><p>The Galleon's principal trade-off is its limited protection. Against most BattleMechs the vehicle relies on speed and maneuvering rather than durability, and it suffers badly when forced into sustained engagements against heavier tanks. The ICE power plant requires integrated power amplifiers to drive the laser armament. The GAL-102 addressed many of these shortcomings by replacing the ICE with a fusion engine, adding ferro-fibrous armor protection, upgrading to pulse and medium laser armament, and fitting a Beagle Active Probe, substantially improving the design's sustained combat capability and reconnaissance value.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Marian Hegemony's standardized Galleon variant uses an ICE power plant to retain the original vehicle's speed while mounting an entirely rocket-based armament suite. Four front-mounted Rocket Launcher/10s and a turret combination of paired Machine Guns and a Rocket Launcher/20 provide overwhelming short-range firepower at the cost of any sustained engagement capability. Hadrian Mechanized Industries on Pompey produces this as a newly manufactured design rather than a refit, standardizing the Marian Hegemony's light armor inventory without relying on Free Worlds League-sourced parts. The shared ammo bin for the machine guns keeps logistics manageable for Periphery supply chains.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Production of the Galleon began at Brooks Incorporated's armaments plants across the Free Worlds League in 2692, with early facilities on Holt, Andurien, Irian, and Kendall, and a licensed production line at Ceres Metals Industries on Indicass in Capellan space. The tank served throughout the Star League era as a backbone light vehicle for planetary militias and support formations, earning a solid reputation for cost-effective performance if not outright battlefield dominance.</p><p>During the Amaris Civil War the Galleon proved its worth in the rapid advances and urban fighting that characterized much of that conflict. After Operation Exodus, the tank dispersed widely. Large numbers stationed in Periphery garrisons fell to House Marik and House Kurita as those states consolidated their borders, giving the Draconis Combine a substantial Galleon fleet that eventually produced the GAL-200 field variant.</p><p>The Succession Wars hit production hard. The original Ceres Metals line at Holt was destroyed during the First Succession War, eventually rebuilt by Brooks in 2892. The Andurien War of the 3030s proved nearly fatal to the company in a different way. Thomas Marik, dissatisfied with the Galleon's performance and eager to modernize the Free Worlds League Military, drastically reduced procurement orders. The cuts nearly bankrupted Brooks Incorporated outright. Forced to reorganize, Brooks downsized operations, decommissioned the Holt facility, and expanded the Irian plant to absorb production. To recover financial footing the company began developing an upgraded variant, submitting the improved design to the FWLM procurement department. After nearly three years of evaluation, limited production of the GAL-102 began in 3043, reaching full-scale production in 3048.</p><p>The GAL-102's success drew buyers beyond the League, with the Federated Commonwealth and Draconis Combine becoming primary customers. The Blakist era saw Vicore Armorworks on Terra develop two specialized electronic warfare variants, while the post-Jihad period brought both the Republic of the Sphere and the reformed Free Worlds League states into the Galleon's production network. By the ilClan era, Clan Wolf's acquisition of the Amity facility had added a distinctly Clan-technology variant to the family, and Maxwell Planetary Defense Consortium had extended the chassis into scout and infantry transport roles. From frontier militia to Republic regulars, the Galleon proved one of the most durable light vehicle designs in the Inner Sphere.</p>
</history>

